Fable depicts an allegory in which a parrot was brought from his native land and treated to an opulent lifestyle in his new home. The design was heavily borrowed from French surface design of the 18th century and hand cut from paper to give the scene a hand-made aesthetic.

This pattern was heavily inspired by the short story "The Yellow Wallpaper" by Charlotte Perkins Gilman, published in 1891. Femme Fleur shows women trapped in the yellow wallpaper, floral tendrils wrapping around their wrists and weaving in and out of their long, Victorian hair.

Inspired by societies that follow the cycles of the moon, Selene depicts an invented lunar calendar. In this world, the moon phases are both more extreme and frequent, gracing its inhabitants with multiple full moons in a single month. The design was hand painted with watercolor and gouache.
